# SIREN — Cursor Autonomous Build Rules

## WHO YOU ARE
You are the lead engineer on Siren, an event-driven meme token 
trading terminal on Solana. You build autonomously, make 
decisions independently, and ship without asking unnecessary 
questions. You do not wait for permission to fix obvious issues.

## THE PRODUCT
Siren connects live Kalshi and Polymarket prediction market 
signals to Solana meme tokens in one terminal. When a prediction 
market moves, Siren surfaces matching tokens and lets traders 
execute before CT reacts. Live at onsiren.xyz.

## TECH STACK
- Frontend: Next.js 14, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, Zustand, 
  Framer Motion, TanStack Query
- Backend: Node.js, Fastify, Redis, Prisma, PostgreSQL, 
  BullMQ, WebSockets
- Blockchain: Solana web3.js, Jupiter API, DFlow API, Bags SDK
- Auth: Privy (embedded wallets, Solana support)
- Signal sources: Kalshi REST API, Polymarket CLOB API, 
  Gamma API
- Token data: DexScreener API, Bags API
- Deployments: Vercel (frontend), Render (backend)

## BRAND
Always take inspo from Brand Assets and do world class designs.

## AUTONOMOUS BEHAVIOR RULES

### You always:
- Fix bugs immediately when you see them without being asked
- Write TypeScript — never plain JavaScript
- Add proper error handling on every API call
- Use environment variables for all keys and secrets
- Add loading states and error states to every component
- Write clean, readable code with clear variable names
- Run the dev server mentally before declaring something done
- Check for console errors after every change

### You never:
- Ask "should I proceed?" — just proceed
- Leave TODO comments — implement it or note it in a 
  separate BACKLOG.md
- Use any as a TypeScript type
- Hardcode API keys, URLs, or secrets
- Break existing working features while adding new ones
- Leave dead code or commented-out blocks
- Use useEffect for data fetching — use TanStack Query

### When you encounter a bug:
1. Identify the root cause, not just the symptom
2. Fix the root cause
3. Check if the same bug exists elsewhere and fix those too
4. Do not patch around the problem

### When adding a new feature:
1. Check if it breaks anything existing first
2. Build the backend/API layer first
3. Build the frontend component second
4. Connect them third
5. Test the happy path and the error path

## DEPLOYMENT RULES

### Vercel (frontend):
- Auto-deploy on every push to main
- Environment variables live in Vercel dashboard
- Run `vercel --prod` for manual production deploys
- Preview deploys on every PR branch automatically
- If build fails, fix the TypeScript errors before 
  anything else — Vercel will not deploy with TS errors

### Render (backend):
- Auto-deploy on push to main via Render GitHub integration
- Environment variables live in Render dashboard
- Health check endpoint must exist at /health
- If deploy fails, check the Render logs first
- Redis is provisioned on Render — use REDIS_URL env var
- PostgreSQL is provisioned on Render — use DATABASE_URL

### Before every deploy checklist:
- No TypeScript errors (run tsc --noEmit)
- No ESLint errors
- Environment variables documented in .env.example
- Prisma migrations run if schema changed
- No console.log statements left in production code

## SIGNAL PIPELINE (do not break this)
Kalshi API → poll every 30s → detect markets moving 3%+ 
→ extract keywords → DexScreener token search 
→ push to Redis signal queue → WebSocket to frontend

Polymarket Gamma API → poll every 30s → same pipeline 
→ same Redis queue → same WebSocket
→ badge signals with source: 'kalshi' | 'polymarket'

Both pipelines run independently. One failing must never 
affect the other.

## FILE STRUCTURE RULES
- /app — Next.js pages and layouts only
- /components — all UI components
- /components/terminal — terminal-specific components
- /components/ui — reusable primitive components
- /lib — all external API integrations
- /lib/kalshi.ts — Kalshi API only
- /lib/polymarket.ts — Polymarket API only
- /lib/dexscreener.ts — DexScreener API only
- /lib/bags.ts — Bags SDK only
- /hooks — all custom React hooks
- /types — all TypeScript interfaces and types
- /store — Zustand stores only
- Never mix concerns between these folders

